For years the good people of Walney have been slaves, slaves for the South! Our homes were built for the men of the shipyard, the work of that yard went to the South! The ships went to the South, our money went to the South and what did we get in return for our labour, determination and resolve to carry on? We got higher rent, higher taxes, higher bills and misrepresentation in the media. I ask you, where is the BBC situated? London! For Walney to survive in the neglect from the South we must become a free republic, and I plan to lead us away from the neglect of the South and into a prosperous future.

It is my goal to fight for our independence and expand our borders into mailand Furness. I plan to do this peacefully so as to spare any of our good men losing their lives in the fight for freedom. I will debate freedom in Westminster and try to get a vote for the freedom of our nation. We will then take Barrow so we can have the shipyard and farmland, we will use this to sell ships and create a naval fleet to defend our shores and take the coastal wind farm. Any excess energy will be sold. With our new navy and resurgence of farming I will create jobs for more people. I will also ensure we meet every climate goal we can and make Walney one of the most environmentally friendly nations in the world. 

I will make schools focus more on DT to help young people get jobs within Walney, I will lower choosing class options to the end of year 8 so that our young people can get the education they want

[11/03/2022 10:51 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907 (pinned)
Rules so far:
Repeated letters have a line over them.

D(e) is only used when a vowel comes after "de".

If a word starts with A, followed by a consonant, it should become an E.

If the endling letter to a word is c, and the previous letter is a vowel, it becomes C(h).

If c is the first letter of a word, followed  by a vowel, it becomes a K.

If an O is followed by a vowel, it makes an "Oh" sound.

If c is the first letter of a word, followed by a vowel, then it becomes a K.

If the letter after a consonant is E, then the consonant goes in front of it.

If a vowel is followed by another vowel, then the second vowel should be silent.

If a vowel is silent, it should be replaced with an apostrophe.

https://linguavirtua.com/how-to-create-your-own-constructed-language-conlang
How to Create Your Own Constructed Language (Conlang) - LinguaVirtua
The beauty of language is that it is highly adaptable: they evolve as new generations come, words are added to a lexicon, and grammar rules are constantly adjusted. Furthermore, both professional linguists and language enthusiasts alike can construct an entirely new language of their own from scratch. Often referred to as conlangs (constructed l...
https://images-ext-2.discordapp.net/external/-JtJ-BLK3twYHrmur8yFf5-AAhw5jyOZCrx7Z2sioV8/https/linguavirtua.com/og.jpeg


[11/03/2022 11:12 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
1. Decide how you want your language to ‚Äúsound‚Äù like
Start with your phonology‚Äîhow do you want your language to sound like? Draw inspiration from existing languages. 

For example, German and Arabic are generally harsh-sounding languages, while French and Italian sound ‚Äúsweeter‚Äù and more feminine.


[11/03/2022 11:12 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
2. Determine your consonants and vowels
Your phonology goes hand in hand with your phonotactics‚Äîthe way consonants and vowels go together. 

It‚Äôs important to note that ‚Äúhard‚Äù languages are those that predominantly use guttural consonants such as /K/ and /G/ with fewer connecting vowels. ‚ÄúSoft‚Äù languages, on the other hand, tend to use more vowels than consonants.


[11/03/2022 11:12 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
3. Create your words
This is where language creation gets more fun: creating your own words or lexicon. 

With your phonology and phonotactics to guide you, you can derive your vocabulary from any language that makes sense to your conlang. For example, since the creators of the Dothraki wanted the language to sound harsh, many elements of the conlang were inspired by the Arabic language, including its vocabulary. 

Consider your syllables and stresses as well. For example, do some words change in terms of how it is inflected depending on the mood or context?


[11/03/2022 11:12 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
**WE SHOULD PROBABLY MAKE SOME VOWELS**


[11/03/2022 11:14 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Vowels are letters that make a noise for which you don't need have any contact in your mouth. Essentially noises that you make with only your throat. In all other letters, you move your lips or tongue or anything else.

I met a traveller from an antique land,
Who said‚Äî‚ÄúTwo vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desert. . . . Near them, on the sand,

And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,

[11/03/2022 11:36 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Rules so far:
Repeated letters have a line over them.

D(e) is only used when a vowel comes after "de".

If a word starts with A, followed by a consonant, it should become an E.

If the endling letter to a word is c, and the previous letter is a vowel, it becomes C(h).

If c is the first letter of a word, followed  by a vowel, it becomes a K.

If an O is followed by a vowel, it makes an "Oh" sound.

If c is the first letter of a word, followed by a vowel, then it becomes a K.

If the letter after a consonant is E, then the consonant goes in front of it.

If a vowel is followed by another vowel, then the second vowel should be silent.

If a vowel is silent, it should be replaced with an apostrophe.

[11/04/2022 12:37 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
English and Dutch also have their similarities in grammar, however, they do not come without some differences.

The Dutch verb system is similar to the English one although there are some exceptions. For example, the Dutch do not use the auxiliary in question or negations. So, a Dutch studying entry-level English may phrase a question in the following way: ‚ÄúWhere you come from?‚Äù, ‚ÄúHow you like the food?‚Äù or ‚ÄúI drink not beer‚Äù. There is also no continuous tense in the Dutch language which can lead to translation errors like: ‚ÄúI ate a supper when you rang the bell‚Äù!

Another difference between the two languages is that English uses past simple in order to describe a past activity that started and ended in the past. Conversely, Dutch used the present perfect in order to express the same action.

Here is an example:

English ‚Äì  My cousin went to Spain last year. Dutch ‚Äì  My cousin has gone to Spain last year.

The more basic the word the shorter, so simple ideas like sky and land are very small when more complicated ideas like surgery and physics are longer because those concepts come later in a languages life


[11/07/2022 9:25 PM] 5298_
Language follows human achievement, newer words are based around newer concepts and if we're having a built upon language where parts of words make other words then more complicated words will be longer because they're talking many concepts from many words

This pattern, in Irish Gaelic, is called ‚ÄúCaol le caol, leathan le leathan‚Äù. Let me explain: If the vowels ‚Äúa‚Äù, ‚Äúo‚Äù or ‚Äúu‚Äù are immediately followed by one or more consonants, then any vowel immediately following those consonants will also be ‚Äúa‚Äù, ‚Äúo‚Äù, or ‚Äúu

[11/07/2022 9:41 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907

Before the great mountains and vast oceans of the world there was only a night. This night was called Nikht and it was ruled by an emperor of the same name. Nikht and his wife together conceived the realm of Nikht. They then conceived the moon and all the stars to decorate their new realm but there was a fault with the moon, it started to melt. The dew of the moon formed a tall white stag called Motstahm. Motstahm was so cold that he kicked and ran to warm himself, leaving great footprints on the moon as he did so. Doing this, Motstahm got so warm that his antlers began to glow and lit up half of Nikht. This new part of Nikht was called Dayg. Still, Motstahms‚Äôs antlers were so bright they made a flaming entity also called Dayg. Sufficiently warm, Motstahm travelled back to the moon but Dayg wanted to stay with her father and chased after him but was too slow to catch him, to this day Dayg chases Motstahm wanting her father.

The Connaught Rangers (88th Regiment of Foot, "the Devil's Own") was a hard fighting Irish regiment of the British Army. This song was composed by Lt. Charles Martin, who served with the Rangers from 1888-1893.

Growing Human Neurons Connected to a Computer
Neurons are amazing little microbes capable of learning and making decisions. Modern AI tries to take inspiration from living neurons, but why settle for the synthetic version? [11/11/2022 1:01 AM] 5298_

[11/11/2022 1:01 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
An analogue of a tiny, expanding universe has been created out of extremely cold potassium atoms. It could be used to help us understand cosmic phenomena that are exceedingly difficult to directly detect, such as pairs of particles that may be created out of empty space as the universe expands.

Markus Oberthaler at Heidelberg University in Germany and his colleagues cooled more than 20,000 potassium atoms in a vacuum, using lasers to slow them down and lower their temperature to about 60 nanokelvin, or 60 billionths of a degree kelvin above absolute zero.

At this temperature, the atoms formed a cloud about the width of a human hair and, instead of freezing, they became a quantum, fluid-like phase of matter called a Bose-Einstein condensate. Atoms in this phase can be controlled by shining light on them ‚Äì using a tiny projector, the researchers precisely set the atoms‚Äô density, arrangement in space and the forces they exert on each other.

By changing these properties, the team made the atoms follow an equation called a space-time metric, which, in an actual, full-scale universe, determines how curved it is, how fast light travels and how much light must bend near very massive objects. This is the first experiment that has used cold atoms to simulate a curved and expanding universe, says Oberthaler.


[11/11/2022 1:01 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
When the researchers used their projector to make atoms mimic an expanding universe, the atoms moved in exactly the kind of ripple pattern that would be expected if pairs of particles were popping into existence ‚Äì a phenomenon called particle pair production. The researchers say this suggests that the particle pairs can be produced in an expanding universe, like our own.

Alessio Celi at the Autonomous University of Barcelona in Spain says that the new experiment is a very precise playground for putting together quantum effects and gravity. Physicists don‚Äôt quite know how the two combine in the universe we live in, but experiments with ultracold atoms may let them try out some ideas, and they could inspire new targets for observations in our much larger and more complex cosmos, he says.

Stefan Floerchinger at the University of Jena in Germany, who was part of the research team, says that future experiments with the same system could lead to a better understanding of quantum properties of our universe.

Everything will have been. There will be a time when nothing new will ever happen. Everything that has ever happened will all melt together into the silent cacophony, the unblinking pupil. The mass of everything, the great mystery. This will happen. And you won‚Äôt exist. Your history and future will be forgotten, incinerated and lost. We won‚Äôt be. The God that rules the heavens and breathes life into all; will destroy us and kill herself in a glory of colour. The Earth's losses and victories, her parasite that rules over her with complete dominion that has crafted a history and future for itself will be destroyed with nothing left. We call this mortality. The notion that one will die is terrifying for most, and debilitating for some. But mortality is not just the notion that one will die, it is the notion that their kinship will die, their friends, enemies, communities, future. Everything that will ever be will die. This can be a horrific notion. Mortality is a sickening word that infects us all. Some try to cheat it with a legacy, this too is fleeting. for when the people that know this legacy die and the statues fall and the books decay, so too will that legacy. A legacy is a mortal man extending his life, not negating death, just prolonging it until after they rot. Then everything will rot and none of this will matter. 

I wrote this a little while ago and I thought it was fitting for the conversation

The calculation of the ESI is based on only a few parameters: radius, density, escape velocity, and surface temperature. For exoplanets, the ESI is based on even fewer parameters: stellar flux, and either radius or mass.

[11/13/2022 3:21 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Westmeath Examiner, November, 1921"Grounded Their Arms."Barrack Scene Described by Ex-Connaught Ranger.Private Daly's Death.The "Freeman's Journal" publishes the following; What took place in an Indian barracks last year, when the Connaught Rangers, one of whom was subsequently shot, protested against the treatment that was then being meted out to their countrymen at home is briefly described in a letter that has arrived in Tullamore from an ex-member of the corps, who, for the part he played, is now serving a term of imprisonment in Liverpool. It is significant that Mr James Clarke, Tullamore, to whom the letter is addressed, is now in Ballykinlar Internment Camp.The writer, Joseph Walsh, a native of Tullamore, says;--"I am writing to see if you will be kind enough to give me any news of my family, especially my poor old parents. The only thing I am frightened about is my mother's position. Thank God I can hold up my head and say that I was not sent to prison for anything disgraceful. I expect you have seen all about the case in the newspapers, but I can assure you that you or anybody also did not see the truth of this affair in print; nor will it ever be known until some of us get released. "You know it would be impossible to tell you all in this letter, Simply 410 men grounded their arms, protesting against the attitude of the Government in Ireland; 105 were tried by general courtmartial; 64 were convicted, the sentences ranging from death to 12 month's imprisonment; 14 were condemned to death; 13 were reprieved. One was shot on November, 2nd, 1920. The remainder came home and are in Maidstone Convict Prison, Walton Prison, Manchester and Working prisons.


[11/13/2022 3:21 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
"Jack Lloyd, myself, and two other Birr men represented King's County, the other chaps came from Sligo, Boyle, Roscommon, Roscrea, Westmeath. The chap that was shot (Daly) came from Tyrrellspass-he was a brave man, He was exactly 21 years and 11 months old when he died; I cooked all his food up to the day he died. Jack Lloyd, was acquitted." I got five years penal servitude, which was reduced to 3 years, and I have 12 months to complete from November 13th, and I do not expect any day knocked off until the Irish question is finished. Remember me to all the boys. I am allowed to write only once in four months."

[11/19/2022 8:42 PM] 5298_
From 1564 to 1642 one of the world's greatest minds, and Italy's pride and joy, walked the streets. This man‚Äôs life was full of extraordinary achievement but something less known was his controversy. From dutchesses to the Roman Inquisition itself, everyone had something to say about the theory of Galileo Galilei. 

Galilei was a physicist, engineer and mathematician. Arguably his most famous invention - which is rarely attributed to him - is the telescope. Galileo would publish his observations in his telescope in 1610 in the ‚ÄúSidereus Nuncius‚Äù. This is where Galileo‚Äôs problems would come from. 

In the seventeenth century most people believed in Aristotelian Geocentrism. Mainly this was for religious regions, people believed that the Earth was naturally the most important planet because all of God's creatures lived on it. This set the stage for Galileo‚Äôs controversy, unlike others of the day, he believed in heliocentrism. These beliefs garnered Galileo attention from people who held opposing views. He gained scientific and religious opposition alike. 

The religious opposition first came from The Grand Duchess Christina of Florence who wrote to one of the astronomers friends saying that heliocentrism is contrary to the Bible. This letter made Galileo write to the Grand Duchess saying that heliocentrism actually isn‚Äôt contrary to the Bible and even if it wasn‚Äôt that the Bible is a source of spiritual and moral wisdom and not science.

[11/27/2022 6:03 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Jones had some early successes against British merchant shipping in the Irish Sea. He persuaded his crew on April 17, 1778, to participate in an assault on Whitehaven, the town where his maritime career had begun.[22] Jones later wrote about the poor command qualities of his senior officers (having tactfully avoided such matters in his official report): "'Their object', they said, 'was gain not honor'. They were poor: instead of encouraging the morale of the crew, they excited them to disobedience; they persuaded them that they had the right to judge whether a measure that was proposed to them was good or bad".[23] As it happened, contrary winds forced them to abandon the attempt and drive Ranger towards Ireland, causing more trouble for British shipping on the way.

[12/04/2022 9:53 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
It was the year 2052 and Barrow-in-Furness, a once peaceful town in the northern part of England, had suffered an extremely draconian rule over the past years. The people of Barrow-in-Furness were oppressed and relegated to a state of suffering and misery; their simple lives were ruined by a corrupt government that had been in power since 2026. The town was now ruled by a ruthless dictator, Jason Wilbanks, and his tyrannical regime.

Rylan O'Neill, Will Hunt, and Reece McDonald were three rebels, brought up in a town living in a state of devastation and despair. Rylan was a young man, with a fierce determination, passion for justice and a thirst for adventure. He had an infectious optimism which he used to motivate his comrades. He had been a close friend of Will Hunt since childhood, and was determined to bring an end to the oppressive regime once and for all. Will, on the other hand, was the strategist of the trio, with a sharp analytical mind and a cool head. He accepted the risks that came with rebellion, but was always sure to manage the risks effectively for the greater good. 

Reece McDonald was the third of the rebels; a magnetic character and a natural leader. His impressive aptitude for communication and charisma made him an inspirational figure within the town. He mobilized a multitude of people under the cause and was determined to bring about a revolution.


[12/04/2022 9:53 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
The trio had devised a plan to liberate Barrow-in-Furness from the dictator's rule. After months of preparation, their battle ensued. The rebels swept through the former dictator's palace, and with willpower and courage, the trio valiantly claimed the area from the oppressive rule. 

Finally, after years of misery, the people of Barrow-in-Furness were liberated. As Rylan, Will, and Reece were hailed as heroes, they could feel an immense sense of pride, knowing that this was the result of their fearless and unrelenting efforts. 

The citizens of Barrow-in-Furness were eternally grateful to their pioneers, whom had brought a much-needed sense of hope and freedom to the town. The terrible era had finally come to an end, and the small town of Barrow-in-Furness could look forward to a new, bright future. 

It was a beautiful story of courage, heroism and the relentless pursuit of freedom. Little did any of them know, this was only the beginning for the trio, for their relentless drive for justice was about to take them to new heights.

Good evening, citizens of North Walney 

Today, I am here to address the ongoing situation with South Walney, which threatens the peace and stability of this Island. As you all may know, back in October, the Republic of Walney, our united nation, held an election that sought to remove power from the North. As a result of the President, Reece McDonald, and his government's actions, this prompted our nation to declare independence. It was clear that they only cared for themselves.

Recently, it was noted that South Walney has been building an enormous, intimidating force on the border, that threatens to disrupt the peace and stability of the island. As such, I recommend the government of South Walney remove their troops immediately, as nobody wants to go down a path of death and destruction which a war would bring. 

Furthermore, we mustn't forget the oppression the North has faced from the South. During, the elections, the South Walnesian government denied the basic right to vote, to citizens of the North. This act will never be forgotten, for the significance it holds to us. We shall not let the South Rule over us with an Iron Fist, like they did for many years. We must stand together, to ensure us, as people, shall continue to live on, not oppressed, nor shall we oppress.

Thank you,
President Rylan JC O'Neill

Me and a few other people all over England left society and went to an agreed upon location in the Scottish forest, the people from Cumbria all got there and we started with splitting ourselves into different groups, toolsmiths, hunters, cooks, builders, sowers and gardeners, we then got to work, the toolsmiths making spears and knives and bows for the hunters to go get food for everyone, the builders started making the camp and making the fire, the gardeners looked around for anything to grow and the cooks and sowers waited for the hunters to get back. Then it was basically a socialist utopia, everyone working for the good of everyone, no greed, the hunters got meat and hyde for the camp, the cooks made a fair amount of food for everyone, the builders made places for everyone to live, the sowers made clothes out of the hyde for everyone. It was like clockwork it was amazing. Then when people from further around the country like the south and Wales came we adjusted accordingly

[12/18/2022 1:00 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
From one source: "TRAPPIST-1g is the largest of the planets, with a radius 1.154 times that of Earth. The results, so far, indicate that it is unlikely to have a deep primordial hydrogen atmosphere. Larger gas and ice giants, like Jupiter or Neptune in our own solar system, tend to have such atmospheres. This means that TRAPPIST-1g could have a thinner, more terrestrial-type atmosphere, like that of Earth, Venus or Mars. If so, that would be good for the prospects of possible life, since those are secondary atmospheres, ones that have undergone significant chemical alterations over millions or billions of years. For example, Earth‚Äôs primarily nitrogen atmosphere is largely due to life processes changing it over time."


[12/18/2022 1:00 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
I misinterpreted what they were saying


[12/18/2022 1:14 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
There will also be updates about both TRAPPIST-1b and TRAPPIST-1g given at the upcoming 241st Meeting of the American Astronomical Society in Seattle, Washington (January 8-12, 2023).

From the abstract for TRAPPIST-1b:

In this talk, we present the first high-precision transit spectra of the warm Earth-sized planet TRAPPIST-1b based on two transit observations using NIRISS in SOSS mode on the James Webb Space Telescope. TRAPPIST-1b is the most favorable Earth-sized planet for characterization via transmission spectroscopy among all exoplanets. As such, our observations have the sensitivity to detect a wide range of atmospheres, providing unprecedented insight into the potentially secondary atmosphere on a rocky Earth-sized planet outside the solar system.

[12/21/2022 1:22 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
From the wiki


[12/21/2022 1:22 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
It has been speculated that any hypothetical microorganisms inhabiting the atmosphere, if present, could employ ultraviolet light (UV) emitted by the Sun as an energy source, which could be an explanation for the dark lines (called "unknown UV absorber") observed in the UV photographs of Venus.[42][43] The existence of this "unknown UV absorber" prompted Carl Sagan to publish an article in 1963 proposing the hypothesis of microorganisms in the upper atmosphere as the agent absorbing the UV light.[44]

In August 2019, astronomers reported a newly discovered long-term pattern of UV light absorbance and albedo changes in the atmosphere of Venus and its weather, that is caused by "unknown absorbers" that may include unknown chemicals or even large colonies of microorganisms high up in the atmosphere.[45][46]

In January 2020, astronomers reported evidence that suggests Venus is currently (within 2.5 million years from present) volcanically active, and the residue from such activity may be a potential source of nutrients for possible microorganisms in the Venusian atmosphere.[47][48][49]

In 2021, it was suggested the color of "unknown UV absorber" match that of "red oil" - a known substance comprising a mix of organic carbon compounds dissolved in concentrated sulfuric acid.

[01/02/2023 2:26 AM] 5298_
1) Ursa Major was shining bright in the sky, the lazy bear stalked through the abyss as though it was making its way to a great feast of hunny off the horizon line and there so too shall we be, everything is ready as we board the ship to set sail to the horizon.
2) The water gently moved in the wind, almost in a welcoming way, and the reflections of the stars swam with it
3) The vessel rocked gently with the water, the quiet whispering of the waves against the hull was the only sound in the empty port.
4) watching as we say goodbye to what we know, we'll see you again one day, but the sea is calling, it's time to go
5) We sail south, heading into the sea ready to make our journey when the wind picks up, mumbling its curses into our sails and making the water chew at the hull.
6) it felt as though it was telling us to leave, but we couldn't, we were called by the waves and welcomed by the sea, it would be rude to leave now.
7) Our defiance of the winds call must have angered Boreas himself because the north wind then blew with a great ire, paining the mast and making the sea crash viciously
8) we thought the sea was our friend, but it turned on us so suddenly, what we thought we could trust now betraying us
9) The wind grew violent, straining the sails to their limit when the vessel began to lift, her bow lifting into the air before we arose out of the ocean, as though crashing on a rock but all that was under us was the air.
10) we moved on, growing higher by the second, looking down to see everything become smaller, something that is so large, now comparable to a seed
11) I felt sick as I leaned over the deck, seeing the Mediterranean fleeing away from us, Iberia in sight now as we flew up to Uranus; his great mass blanketing the world, I wondered if Zeus would paint our peculiar voyage in the same sky we sailed to.
12) from sailing the sea to sailing the sky, the view had definitely changed, from the place we knew so well to a place like a stranger to us

Now you probably think I am going to talk about completely getting rid of the school system, however that is not my intention. My intention is to bring light to the changes that need to occur.

[01/12/2023 10:00 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
School. A place of learning. As quoted by this school it's a "place of learning, love and compassion". But is it really? At the end of the day, you spend years and years of your life sitting in a classroom for about 6 hours a day, where your actions are policied by a teacher, where the seconds tick by as slow as a sloth. Now you probably think I am going to talk about completely getting rid of the school system. However, that is not my intention; I intend to bring light to the changes that need to occur.

To begin with, we must discuss the time at which we are forced to come into school. Coming into school at 8:30 am will and does have stark consequences on the mental well-being of children. Every single day, you will hear students complaining of being tired, but each time it is blamed on a poor sleep schedule. In actuality, during adolescence, the internal clock of a person is shifted by upwards of 2-3 hours. This leads to a child who previously slept at 9pm to start sleeping at 10pm, 11pm, 12am or later. A developing teenager needs around 9-10 hours of sleep, and as such, waking up at 7am to get ready for school can have dire effects on learning. Research has proven that a 10:30am start to school drastically improves performance.

I understand that it is in the School‚Äôs best interest to stop damage from being caused to them, and to stop congregations of people forming there after break, normally to skip lessons. [01/13/2023 9:57 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
School. A place of learning. As quoted by this school it is a "place of learning, love and compassion". But is it really? At the end of the day, you spend years and years of your life sitting in a classroom for about 6 hours a day, where your actions are policed by a teacher, where the seconds tick by as slow as a sloth. Now you probably think I am going to talk about completely getting rid of the school system. However, that is not my intention; I intend to bring light to the changes that need to occur. 

To begin with, we must discuss the time at which we are forced to come into school. Coming into school at 8:30 am will and does have stark consequences on the mental well-being of children. Every single day, you will hear students complaining of being tired, but every single time it is blamed on a poor sleep schedule. In actuality, during adolescence, the internal clock of a person is shifted by upwards of 2-3 hours. This leads to a child who previously slept at 9pm to start sleeping at 10pm, 11pm, 12am or later. A developing teenager needs around 9-10 hours of sleep, and as such, waking up at 7am to get ready for school can have dire effects on learning. Research has proven that a 10:30am start to school drastically improves performance, leading to better mental health and behaviour all around the school.


[01/13/2023 9:58 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
** **
Second of all, I would like to speak about toilets. How are teachers allowed to refuse access to them? I understand that it is in the School‚Äôs best interest to stop damage from being caused to them, and to stop congregations of people forming there after break, normally to skip lessons. But, why should everyone be punished for a minority‚Äôs actions? Why should we sit there for upwards of one hour and thirty-five minutes just to use such a common thing in our lives? Refusal to use the School‚Äôs toilets goes against the Human Right to Sanitation (Article 11 of the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights or ICESCR, ‚Äúthe right of everyone to an adequate standard of living for himself and his family‚Äù) but for some reason, the School System appears to be granted the right to break Human Rights. Why are they still allowed to operate as such? 

Another issue with toilets is how utterly disgusting they are. Everyone in the school is familiar with the disgusting grime that crawls along the floor and climbs the walls, the miasma of the bathrooms which coats your nostrils as though it were mucus. There are always crowds of people there during break and dinnertime, which can get rather irritating, and by the end of it there is rubbish plaguing the floor, toilet paper clinging onto the walls among a seemingly never-ending list of damage. All of this should be preventable, yet it somehow is not. 
** **


[01/13/2023 9:58 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Toilet Passes are another big issue, because they do not exactly achieve anything, but make students feel more frustrated. I understand people may have disabilities which affect their bladder, or bowels. Pass holders are immediately allowed to go to the toilet, but people who do not hold a pass will probably be refused. When they are refused, they become more upset about it, seeing a peer being able to freely use the toilets, and it becomes more likely for them to concentrate less. Why would you want someone not to work when the whole point of school is to learn and to work? Along with this, some students use this to their advantage and go off to who knows where.

Thirdly, the punishment system is flawed. A major part of the education system is the punishment system. Punishment is meant to be a form of reinforcing a certain behaviour, however, for the most part, it fails to achieve its own goals. Unless someone is from a super strict household, being punished is received as a joke; laughable. It is a great example of negative reinforcement. You remove a stimulus from the student‚Äôs environment, this may be that they are no longer able to see their friends, or they have to stay after school and this is to decrease their disruptive behaviour. This seems to work in theory, but in reality, a whole other story is told. When a student is punished, it makes them have some form of anger towards that teacher. This anger needs to release itself and, as such, this release comes in the form of disrupting lessons, being horrible to people and wanting to do damage to the school. Eventually, people who also agree that a teacher may be annoying will begin to repeat them and slowly the whole school escalates into chaos.


[01/13/2023 9:58 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
** **
Behaviour points are a ridiculous concept and I am not sure why they were implemented. The idea is good in theory, students are punished with behaviour points because having behaviour points show where they are going wrong, it also informs their parents about what they have done wrong, and allows any issues to be dealt with at home. However, a lot of students do not see behaviour points as a punishment, but rather as an achievement; like medals of sorts. This leads to students trying to see who can get the most behaviour points, and, obviously, misbehaviour. Now, you may think that this should apply to achievement points, but you would be wrong. In school, anyone who performs well is bombarded with insults just because they are getting on, and this leads to people finding it weird to compete for achievement points. They aren‚Äôt seen as achievement points, but just as points with no social benefits.

Erin's Flag - Irish Rebel Song (Lyrics)
"Erin's Flag" is an Irish Rebel song about the contribution of each part of Ireland to the the national struggle, from Rebel Cork to the counties Down and Antrim. Each province of Ireland has produced its own martyrs in the fight for freedom, deserving of recognition. 

Original Artist: Ray McAreavey

[01/17/2023 7:37 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Over the last few decades, the education system has continued to spiral downhill. It fails thousands in it‚Äôs main job: to provide a good and clear education to students. Students arrive at school everyday, expecting to be taught to an adequate standard. However, this is not the case. I believe that the school systems requires reform and change urgently. If this is not achieved. the youth of this nation will fall behind on many opportunities. However, I am not here to call for the removal of the school system; I believe that is an utterly idiotic idea.

Firstly, students are forced into school at ridiculous times. This must be changed, as for the vast majority of students, sleeping later on is the standard. During adolescence, the internal clock of a person shifts by upwards of 2-3 hours; this means a child who previously slept at 9pm would start sleeping at around 11pm, 12am or later. At most, a student of this nature would be getting 7 hours of sleep. They are missing out on hours of sleeping, falling behind the 9 hour mark, required for efficient bodily functions, like: concentrating, growth and development of the Brain. Studies have proven time and time again that a 10:30am start to school can improve performance, can improve mental health (a growing issue in younger generations) and behaviour all around. Why would school want to impact their student‚Äôs life and career in such a way? British Schools ought to change their starting times.


[01/17/2023 7:58 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Secondly, the toilets are a disgrace, especially in this school. First off, why are teachers 
granted the permission to refuse access to something which is so vital to the day-to-day function of someone? I understand that the school‚Äôs interest is to keep property from being damaged, and to stop crowds of people from forming there after break and dinner. However, why is it that everyone must be punished for the actions of a minority? Why are we forced to wait for upwards of one hour and thirty-five minutes just to use them? In fact, refusing to allow this is a violation of Human Rights, specifically the Human Right to Sanitation (read Article 11 of the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights or ICESCR, ‚Äúthe right of everyone to an adequate standard of living for himself and his family‚Äù). But, for some reason these breaches of Human Rights are acceptable in the eyes of OFSTED, and the government. Some students, including myself, refuse to drink a lot in school in case I need to go to the toilet, because I know I will likely be refused access. Furthermore, the walls and floor in both bathrooms are crawling with grime, and the miasma it releases coats your nose as though it were mucus. Why is nothing being done to ensure the cleanliness of the bathrooms? Why is it that between break times, they are not cleaned? Maybe they are, but to the degree they are cleaned is not clear, as to the naked eye and nose there is no difference.

A uniform so simple in its style
It's got no braid of gold or silk or no hat with feathered plume 
Yet my mother has kept it all the while 
One day she made me try it on, a wish of mine for years
"In memory of your father, dear" she said 
And when I put the Sam Browne on she was smiling through her tears
As she placed the broad black brimmer in my head

By the careless whisk of many's a mountain breeze

[01/31/2023 11:58 PM] 5298_
Tall trees slice the little slight glimpses of sunlight like rationed bread. Vast deserts of virgin snow stretch past infinity in every direction. It suffocates all life under it. The blizzard's cold air freezes my breath and stings my lungs until they turn opiate and numb. I trudge forward, only the wind and the crunching snow to listen to. I move because I fear what will happen if I stop; fear the pointlessness of walking this far just to turn back. No, I keep going

I ruth the trees, their only hope for warmth being self-immolation. I assemble their discarded limbs into a heap ready for praise to Prometheus. I take the thick glove off to get the match; when it is stolen by Hel's tempest. My exposed hand quickly numbs and loses most of its movement. Fire is my only hope. Sparks fly and the match is lit, but as quick as Minas, it is blown out.

The day dies. I can't move any further. Laying with my defeat, I stare at the billion brilliant burning stars. I think of their warmth. I fear what will happen next. Cold seeps into my marrow. I am become cold itself. In the foggy distance, I see a horse as white as the snow, with a familiar rider. He has come to take me now

[02/01/2023 12:26 AM] Bradley Walsh#1907
The harsh sun bled it‚Äôs final rays over the distant ember hills. The dusty air scratched at my raw, hoarse throat as it rolled through the flat, barren plain. The uncomfortable and coarse sand crunched with any slight movement, as it built itself around me as though leaves on a windy autumn day. The hot, desert sun dropped beneath the horizon, dragging night with it. My dying fire glowed dimly in the distance, as I felt death glaring at me. My time was up. My hand was maroon with blood and my white shirt stained as my life slipped away through the craters in my stomach. They laughed at me, reminding me of the encounter with my rival. A wave of peace rushed over me, it was as warm as the waters of the Gulf of Mexico. I embraced my end and my vision began to blur and distort as I felt myself being dragged away. My limbs were paralysed by the weight that fate was bearing down on me. Any attempts at breathing were futile, as my body grew too weak. I took one last deep breathe. The stars finally faded. What was once one of the most wanted men in the west was now a lonely corpse under the dark blanket of the night.

[02/20/2023 10:29 PM] 5298_
Oasis

Thousands of kilometers of desert encompass me. Every centimeter containing dozens of grains of sand. The sun exudes her unbearable heat upon me. The sand consumes it and burns my feet as I walk. Great dunes, like waves in a tempest, form the landscape. Water is a long gone luxury to me now. The only way is forward. Or backwards; I can't tell anymore. All I know is the discomfort. My legs ache and my skin blisters at the sweltering force of the sun. 

Salvation can be seen a few miles away but I pin it to mirage. I must keep pushing in whatever direction this is. Water must be just beyond the horizon, I tell myself. That makes no sense, the horizon stays at the same distance. Water will never come, I realize. What if I have become so deluded that mirage masquerades as oasis and oasis masquerades as mirage. Truth becomes lie, lie becomes truth. No matter the power upon me lie and truth must be but what then, if truth becomes lie? Surely I will die in this absurd condition of truths and lies and balance and deceit. 

Thousands of kilometers of desert encompass me. Every centimeter containing dozens of grains of sand. The ground exudes unbearable heat upon me.


[02/20/2023 10:43 PM] 5298_

{Embed}
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timerio
Timerio
Timerio is a constructed language based on numbers. It was presented to public in 1921 by the Berlin architect Tiemer as a pure literary language and should be used for automated translations. The idea was, that every concept is assigned by a number. The language shows similarities to the Dewey Decimal Classification by Melvil Dewey.

[02/26/2023 3:24 AM] 5298_
Of all the trees that grow so fair
Old England to adorn
Greater are none
Beneath the sun
Than Oak and Ash and Thorn
Sing Oak and Ash and Thorn, good sirs
All of a midsummers morn
Surely we sing of no little thing
In Oak and Ash and Thorn

Oak of the clay
Lived many a day
Or ever Aeneas began
Ash of the loam 
Was a lady at home
When Brut was an outlaw man
Thorn of the down 
Saw New Troy town
From which was London born
Witness hereby the ancientry
Of Oak and Ash and Thorn

Sing Oak and Ash and Thorn, good sirs 
All of a midsummers morn
Surely we sing
Of no little thing
In Oak and Ash and Thorn

Yew that is old
In Churchyard mould
He breedeth a mighty bow
Alder for shoes do wise men choose
And beech for cups also
But when ye have killed and ye bowl is spilled 
Your shoes are clean outworn
Back ye must speed
For that ye need 
In Oak and Ash and Thorn

Sing Oak and Ash and Thorn good sirs
All of a midsummers morn
Surely we sing
Of no little thing
In Oak and Ash and Thorn

Ellum, she hates mankind and waits
Till every gust be laid
To drop a limb
On the head of him
That anyway trusts her shade
But whether a lad be sober or sad
Or mellow with ale from the horn
He'll take no wrong 
When he lieth along
'neath Oak and Ash and Thorn 

Sing Oak and Ash and Thorn good sirs
All of a midsummers morn
Surely we sing
Of no little thing
In Oak and Ash and Thorn

Oh, do not tell the priest our plight
Or he would call it a sin
But we've been out in the woods all night
A-conjuring summer in
And we bring you news
By word of mouth
Good news for cattle and corn
Now is the sun 
Come up from the south
With Oak and Ash and Thorn 

Sing Oak and Ash and Thorn good sirs
All of a midsummers morn
England shall bide
Till Judgement Tide
By Oak and Ash and Thorn

{Embed}
English Folk Project
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FvhRMH-l-Sk
English Folk Song - Oak, Ash and Thorn
Oak, Ash and Thorn is an English folk song adapted from Rudyard Kipling's poem 'A Tree Song', which was included in his fantasy book Puck of Pook's Hill. Peter Bellamy set it to music in his album of the same name, the first of many Kipling-inspired albums that would become the signature genre of Bellamy's discography. The poem praises the oak, ...

Your jar of Virginny 
Will cost you a guinea
Which you reckon too much
By five shillings or ten
But light your Churchwarden
And judge it according 
When I've told you the troubles of poor honest men

From the capes of the Delaware
As you are well aware
We sail with tobacco
For England but then
Our own British cruisers
They watch us come through sirs
And they press half a score of these poor honest men

Or if by quick sailing 
Thick weather prevailing 
We leave them behind 
As we do now and then
We're sure of a gun
From each friggat we run from
Which is often destruction for us poor honest men

Broadsides the Atlantic 
We tumble short handed
With shot holes to plug and new canvas to bend
And of the Azures
Dutch, Dons and Monsieurs
Awaiting to terrify poor honest men

Napoleons embargo 
Is laid on all cargo
Which comforts to aid King George may intend
Since roll twist and leaf
All comforts to cheif
They try for to steal it from poor honest men

With no heart for fight
We take refuge in flight 
But fire as we run
Our retreat to defend
Until our stern chasers
Cut up her fore-brasers 
And she flies up the wind from us poor honest men

A man feels the unrelenting urge to reach the summit of a far off mountain at the horizon. His journey takes him across the plains of which he lives and meets many a colourful character and many a beautiful scene. His journey is a turbulent one, he journeys plains, traverses caverns and eventually climbs the mountain. He grows weak as he climbs and it takes him many months. On his fortieth day, he can see his town on the same horizon he used to see the mountain and realizes how far he has come. He climbs still, almost at his long awaited peak. He arrives, half dead with the trials he's faced but ultimately feels it was worth it

[03/27/2023 10:55 PM] Bradley Walsh#1907
Until April 2023 Cumbria will be administered by Cumbria County Council and six district councils: Allerdale, Barrow-in-Furness, Carlisle, Copeland, Eden, and South Lakeland.

In July 2021 the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government announced that, on 1 April 2023, the administrative county will be reorganised into two unitary authorities: one to be known as Cumberland, and the other as Westmorland and Furness. Cumbria County Council and the six districts are to be abolished and their functions transferred to the new authorities.[46] The two new unitary authorities will continue to constitute a ceremonial county named "Cumbria" for the purpose of lieutenancy and shrievalties, being presided over by a Lord Lieutenant of Cumbria and a High Sheriff of Cumbria.[47][48]

[04/12/2023 10:20 PM] 5298_
A place for people to archive any historic facts ( with sources provided ) and talk about anything history related. Facts can be from mainstream or personal history as long as credible sources are provided. For personal history any tangible evidence that will not breach personal privacy should be sourced and if there is none to provide then a primary source will need to be provided. Our mission is to create an extensive, easily accessible archive of all things historic.

[04/13/2023 9:00 PM] 5298_
An AI goes through and checks for a source and organises the fact then it's published. If someone disagrees with a part of the fact they can say why in a complaint. There will be a symbol for when a fact has a complaint and a moderator will read the complaint, check the fact and either delete the fact if it's wrong or delete the complaint and mark the fact as true, when a fact is true it can't have complaints. If someone thinks a fact marked true is false then they can write an email with a link to the fact and why they think it's wrong, if the complaint is wrong the person will be given a mark, five marks and they aren't allowed to upload facts or write complaints

Gothic alphabet
The Gothic alphabet is an alphabet used for writing the Gothic language. Ulfilas (or Wulfila) developed it in the 4th century AD for the purpose of translating the Bible.The alphabet essentially uses uncial forms of the Greek alphabet, with a few additional letters to express Gothic phonology:

Gothic is an extinct East Germanic language that was spoken by the Goths. It is known primarily from the Codex Argenteus, a 6th-century copy of a 4th-century Bible translation, and is the only East Germanic language with a sizeable text corpus. [04/25/2023 12:04 AM] 5298_
A Eulogy to All

Everything will have been.
There will be a time when nothing new will ever happen.
Everything that has ever happened will all melt together into the silent cacophony,
The unblinking pupil.
The mass of everything,
The great mystery.
This will happen. 
And you won‚Äôt exist.
Your history and future will be forgotten, incinerated and lost.
We won‚Äôt be.
The God that rules the heavens and breathes life into all; will destroy us and kill herself in a glory of colour.
The Earth's losses and victories,
Her parasite that rules over her with complete dominion,
That has crafted a history and future for itself,
Will be destroyed with nothing left.
We call this mortality.
The notion that one will die is terrifying for most,
And debilitating for some.
But mortality is not just the notion that one will die,
It is the notion that their kinship will die,
Their friends,
Enemies,
Communities,
Future.
Everything that will ever be will die.
This can be a horrific notion.
Mortality is a sickening word that infects us all.
Some try to cheat it with a legacy, this too is fleeting.
For when the people that know this legacy die, 
And the statues fall,
And the books decay,
So too will that legacy.
A legacy is a mortal man extending his life,
Not negating death,
Just prolonging it until after they rot.
Then everything will rot and none of this will matter.

Psychosis Test
The Psychosis Test is for young people (age 12-35) who feel like their brain is playing tricks on them (seeing, hearing or believing things that don't seem real or quite right).
https://images-ext-1.discordapp.net/external/x74sN3L2AXpIZiiW3hErRJ3RubpYjfJFdLEIaoNenao/https/screening.mhanational.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Social-media-share-preview.png

[05/01/2023 11:17 PM] 5298_
The original concept was that there were these spaces that when no one was looking you could clip out of reality and you'd be sent into this liminal office then you'd have to either 
A) make it through the levels hoping to reach the bottom ( although no one had ever done it and it might be infinite )
B) find a space in the backrooms to clip back out
Each level was completely unique and had a unique entity that would stalk the level, only some of them were hostile, most were violent though but some where only violent when confronted

Wee German Lairdie - Scottish Jacobite Song (Lyrics)
"Wee German Lairdie" is a Scottish Jacobite Song mocking the German king George I and his hobby of gardening. Jacobitism was a political movement that supported the restoration of the legitimate house of Stuart to the throne. I further added to this humerous song by accentuating the German descent and/or connections of later British monarchs.

[06/07/2023 11:14 PM] 5298_
Church of the Godless 

I kept being told about a cathedral in Barcelona called La Sagrada Familia,
My friends would not stop banging on about it,
I grew up in England, I've seen a cathedral of two,
_No_, everyone replied with a significant glare. _This one is different_,

I found myself passing through Barcelona one week and thought what the hell and made it to the cathedral, 
It looked unusual from the outside certainly, 
At least if I went for five minutes that would shut everyone up,

I stood in line with the other tourists grumbling to myself about what a load of nonsense theology is, throwing a little one-man god is dead party,
Then went in
and had to summon most of my strength to stop my legs collapsing,

It was the bridge of an alien starship,
The window was blaring Tommyknockers green, nova star yellow,
The ceiling vaulted in fractals,
The columns reaching right up into Platonism,
And the overriding geometry of it all was from a universe not too distant from our own, but distant enough not to be our universe,

There was no point trying to resist the feeling of reverence, spacetime took a sabbatical,
For the first time in my life I wore an open mouth unironically,
I sat in the nave for maybe three hours just staring up and listening to Ave Maria and began to understand that look on my religious friends' faces when they talk about God,

When I left it wasn't because I was bored,
Rather the wonder was getting too much like when your mouth hurts from smiling,
I walked aimlessly around Barcelona with my soul carbonated,

The sads turned up at some point,
I listened to them for a while and realised it was mostly jealousy,
Jealousy that us godless folks don't have a church, a place to go and be reverent
or much in the way of tradition at all really, no arias or sermons,
Zero doughnuts,
How did we overlook this? I thought, 
 No wonder we have such terrible PR,

[06/07/2023 11:24 PM] 5298_
Come evening I sat on a hill and watched Barcelona getting darker,
Knowing no one there it was all a bit lonely,
Suddenly I remembered a story:

In the 1970s a pair of probes were being constructed,
Voyager 1 and Voyager 2
set to venture in somewhat opposite directions out of the solar system,
Two people working in the project had fallen in love that summer,
Carl Sagan the astronomer and Ann Druyan the creative director,

Together they were searching for the most defining music of the human species 
so those songs might be copied onto golden discs the probes would carry,
Perhaps to be received one day by extraterrestrials,

Though they had never kissed, had never expressed romantic interest in the other, Carl Sagan phones Ann Druyan one afternoon, and, after the most minimal confirmations that the two of them shared an attraction, Carl Sagan said, "So, for keeps?"
They were married soon after,

When the music had been finalised and the project seemed almost complete
they began to wonder if biorhythms could be decoded by an alien race,
And so Ann Druyan's brainwaves were recorded onto those golden records, a primitive snapshot of human consciousness,
And off to interstellar space the probes went,

After Carl Sagan's death now, Ann Druyan says it's a comfort to know the probes are still on their way,
Will keep going lost after we're gone,
Long after our civilization is gone,
Billions of miles distant, billions more to go,
Carrying: 
A mother's first words to her baby,
The songs of the humpback whale,
Beethoven and Louis Armstrong,
And, Ann Druyan confirms, the brain-music of how it felt one summer during the 20th century to be in love,
Offered as a greeting to alien ears a million years from now,

I looked up from the hill to the first constellations appearing for night,
